{{Infobox manuscript <!----------Name----------> | name = Fojnica Armorial | location = [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] <!----------Image----------> | image = Fojnicki grbovnik combined coa.jpg | width = | caption = The [[Division of the field|combined]] coat of arms on the first page of a fictional "Illyrian Empire", based on the one found in the [[Ohmućević Armorial]]. The divisions are labelled with letters as follows: (A) Macedonia, (B) Slavonia, (C) Bosnia (the star-and-crescent of "Illyria" is present in an inescutcheon in the Bosnian coat of arms), (D) Bulgaria, (E) Dalmatia, (F) Serbia, (G) Croatia, (H) Rascia, (I) "Primordia", with an added imperial [[double-headed eagle]] (labelled J)<!--(K) appears to repeat the Bulgarian red lion in an inescutcheon--> <!----------General----------> | Also known as = | Type = | Date = Uncertain | Place of origin = | Language(s) = | Scribe(s) = Stanislav Rubčić | Author(s) = | Compiled by = | Illuminated by = | Patron = | Dedicated to = King [[Stefan Dušan]] <!----------Form and content----------> | Material = | Size = | Format = | Condition = | Script = [[Cyrillic script|Cyrillic]] | Contents = [[Heraldry]]; 139 coats of arms | Illumination(s) = | Additions = | Exemplar(s) = 1 | Previously kept = [[Franciscan monastery in Fojnica]] | Discovered = 1800 | Other = | below = }}
The so-called '''''Fojnica Armorial''''' ([[Bosnian language|Bosnian]], [[Croatian language|Croatian]], [[Serbian language|Serbian]] ''{{lang|hbs|Fojnički grbovnik/Фојнички грбовник}}'', also known as ''{{lang|hbs|Ilirski grbovnik}}'' "Illyrian armorial") is an early modern [[roll of arms]] including heraldry of South Slavic history. The manuscript is named after the [[Franciscan monastery in Fojnica]] where it was kept.
==Dating== *The presence of the manuscript in the Fojnica monastery is first attested in the year 1800.{{cn|date=March 2015}} *[[Alexander Soloviev (historian)|Alexander Soloviev]] dated it to in between 1675 and 1688, i.e. in the context of the revolts against [[History of Ottoman Serbia|Ottoman rule]] during the [[Great Turkish War]]. *Other scholars{{who|date=March 2015}} have proposed dates of the late 16th or early 17th century.<ref>Sima M. Ćirković, ''The Serbs'', Wiley-Blackwell, 2004, {{ISBN|978-0-631-20471-8}}, p. 133.</ref> The title page of the armorial itself [[pseudepigraphy|purports]] a creation date of 1340.
==Importance== The manuscript is an important source of the classical [[heraldry]] of the Balkans peninsula, alongside the [[Korenić-Neorić Armorial]] of 1595, and the "Illyrian Armorial" (Society of Antiquaries of London MS.54) collected by [[Edward Bourchier, 4th Earl of Bath]] before 1637.
==Roll== The manuscript contains a total of 139 coats of arms. It begins with a depiction of the ''[[Theotokos|Bogorodica]]'', saints [[Cosmas and Damian]], and [[Saint Jerome]]. There follows a title page, written in Cyrillic, which attributes the work to one Stanislav Rubčić, in honour of King [[Stefan Dušan]], with the date 1340. There is an added note in Latin, dated 1800, which testifies that the manuscript had been kept in Fojnica monastery "from time immemorial". Then there is as page showing a combined coat of arms consisting of eleven parts. After this, there are ten coats of arms of late medieval realms of the region, [[Macedonia (theme)|Macedonia]] (''Macedoniae''), "[[Illyrism|Illyria]]" (''Vllvriae''), [[Kingdom of Bosnia|Bosnia]] (''Bosnae''), [[Medieval Dalmatian principalities|Dalmatia]] (''Dalmatie''), [[Kingdom of Croatia (medieval)|Croatia]] (''Crovatiae''), [[Banovina of Slavonia|Slavonia]] (''Slavoniae''), [[Second Bulgarian Empire|Bulgaria]] (''Bvlgariae''), [[Kingdom of Serbia (medieval)|Serbia]] (''Svrbiae''), [[Rascia]] (''Rasciae'') and "Primordia" (''Primordiae''), followed by coats of arms of noble families.
