{{Infobox Radio Show | show_name = Justice Talking | image = | imagesize = | caption = | format = Talk | runtime = 50 minutes | starring = [[Margot Adler]] | country = {{flagicon|United States}} [[United States]] | first_aired = 1999 | last_aired = 2008 | num_episodes = 349 | website = http://www.justicetalking.org/ | home_station = [[National Public Radio]] }} [[Image:Arlen Specter.jpg|thumb|[[Arlen Specter]] while he was being interviewed by [[Margot Adler]] for an episode of Justice Talking on Presidential Signing statements]] '''''Justice Talking''''' was a weekly [[radio show]], [[broadcast syndication#Radio syndication|syndicated]] on [[National Public Radio]] and hosted by [[Margot Adler]], that tackled the law and public policy. A signature element of the program was its debate segment.
It was the flagship of a multi-media civic education initiative online, in print and in classrooms. ''Justice Talking'' was produced by the [[Annenberg Public Policy Center]], a [[think tank]] at the [[Annenberg School for Communication at the University of Pennsylvania|University of Pennsylvania's School for Communications]].
''Justice Talking'''s last show aired on June 30, 2008. According to the producer, the program has ceased production due to lack of funding. <ref>[http://communities.justicetalking.org/blogs/jt/archive/2008/05/30/justice-talking-says-farewell.aspx Justice Talking Says Farewell]</ref>
== Justice Learning web site ==
''Justice Talking'' has a partnership with ''[[The New York Times]]'' Learning Network to produce a free website for students and teachers that discusses legal debates that affect Americans. It is called ''Justice Learning''.<ref>[http://www.justicelearning.org Justice Learning]</ref>
